time_trend_data.indicator_description: Pneumoconiosis is a general term given to any lung disease caused by breathing in certain particles or fibers over a prolonged period. Pneumoconiosis usually results from a workplace exposure  The most common causes of pneumoconiosis include asbestos fibers (asbestosis), silica dust (silicosis), and coal dust (coal workers’ pneumoconiosis or “Black Lung Disease”). There is no cure, but it can be prevented with appropriate respiratory protection.

Compare.graph_title: Trends in  Hospitalizations for Pneumoconiosis - 3-Year Average Annual Rate 2001-2003 to 2016-2018
Compare.y_axis_title: 3-Year Average Annual Rate (per 100,000 residents aged 15 years or older)

info.info_how_calculated: Number of hospitalizations with a pneumoconiosis ICD-9-CM diagnosis code 500 - 505 or an ICD-10-CM diagnosis code J60 - J64, among NYC residents aged 15 years or older, divided by the population of NYC residents aged 15 years or older, expressed as 3-year average annual rate per 100,000 residents.
info.info_source: Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System, U.S. Census Bureau Population Estimates (V2016)
